reviewText: U P D A T E....P L E A S E....N O T E :  This type of film is NOT the type of film I usually see.  An occasional GOOD horror movie, (like the origina (onlyl "Godzilla", or the classic "Carnival of Souls", is more to my liking.  In actual fact, I totally DESPISE "blood and gore quickies", as they lower the sensitivity, (and probably, also the intelligence), of everyone who sees them.  However, I realized that people will keep watching these "nickel dreadfuls", (the film equivalent to the early 20th century cheaply-written and produced novels, called "penny dreadfuls") -- at least until and unless they read reviews showing just HOW bad these movies really are.  I mean, there's a CHANCE they might stop watching them, anyway.  So, in the interests of hopefully raising at least a few people's "MTQ", (Movie Taste Quotient), here is my review of "The Bisbee Cannibal Club"....followed by a few other reviews of such er....movies.  I have endeavoured to make my reviews at least slightly more entertaining than the movies....not, I don't think, a difficult thing to do....  Anyway.....O R I G I N A L......R E V I E WHmmmm...... Has the I.R.S. moved their main base of operations to Bisbee, Arizona?  No -- I guess not, although the title of this movie, (THE BISBEE CANNIBAL CLUB), might, indeed, lead one to believe so.  But this is about flesh-eating, (not wallet-eating) cannibals.  Which is more disgusting?  To me, it's a distinct and total tie!At least this movie has cannibal HUNTERS in it, who want to STOP this awful business, so the movie-makers' ....er, hearts, are in the right place.  But why cannibals would want to eat ONLY vegetarians is beyond me.  Meat gives people vitamins and minerass in greater quantities than most vegetarian diets do.  Oh, well, I suppose even cannibals have differing tastes....The town, BISBEE, is interestingly placed in Arizona.In real life, the KILLER BEES have actually gone into Arizona -- terrorizing Arizonans, and those in nearby states.  My SISTER lives just across the border of Arizona, in Colorado!  I can only hope that the killer bees do NOT mistake humans for other killer bees....and this become cannibal bees!  Or kill humans for any other reasons!Stopping the problem of killer bees would make a wondeful movie.  A title?  "CANNIBAL -- OR CANNOT NIBBLE?"Well, my reviewing talents have seen better reviews.And the silver screen has seen better movies, than THE BISBEE CANNIBAL CLUB.  (And, sadly, worse movies, too...)
summary: C A N N I B A L S......I N......A R I Z O N A....?

reviewText: "The Bisbee Cannibal Club" is an extremely low budget attempt at a comedy, and there are, to be certain, moments that almost made me laugh. But that's really the best I can say for this film.The story involves the discovery by a group of Bisbee, Arizona, locals that there is an organized group of cannibals in the town. The locals form a group to fight against the cannibals (who, by the way, prey only on vegetarians). With this set-up, the film is mostly slapstick, albeit at times gory slapstick. There is a scene, for example, in which one of the cannibals is being chased. He runs past an empty pizza box, stops, goes back to the box, and looks inside in hope of food. That scene was mildly amusing. On a similar level were the multiple bat-to-the-head strikes that were somewhat amusing, though I'm not sure they were intended to be so.The end result is a film that is not especially funny, not in the least bit frightening, and not quite bad enough to make watching the entire thing unbearable. In short, I've seen worse but not often.

reviewText: I want to give this movie to all my vegetarian friends, haha!  This was actually kind of a funny movie.  It's creepy for sure, and there's plenty of human remains...but I was surprised at how funny it was too in a tongue-in-cheek way!  If there were a Cannibal Comedy genre this might fit into it.
